The original grnntee was an Ilhert de Laci, whose great possessions are described in Domesday Book. From him descended other Laeis, who held this fee till the reign of Richard L, when Robert the last of them deceased without issue. On his death the fee de- scended to Albreda de Lizours, of whom there exists a Fine of the fifth year of King Richard showing her in possession, and to whom she disposed of it. The question is how Albreda stood related to the Laci lost seised; and Dugdak, together with the whole body of later genealogists, have followed the Historia Laceiorum, an historical fragment written not ear- lier than the time of King Henry VL, printed in the Monasticon from a Chartulary. The writer of this little piene of history declares Alhreda to have been half-sister ex parte materna to the last of the Lacis.
